Bank of Ireland, Lloyds, Vodafone: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   C o n o r   S u l l i v a n
-- 
2011-07-19T06:42:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/bank-of-ireland-lloyds-vodafone-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index fell 90.85 points, or 1.6 percent, to
5,752.81 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index dropped 1.6
percent, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index retreated 1.3 percent.  Bank of Ireland Plc (BKIR ID):  Standard & Poor’s  downgraded
its rating on Bank of Ireland’s U.K. covered bond program to A-
from A+. The outlook is negative on all the covered bonds issued
under the program, it said in a statement. The stock gained 1
percent to 10.1 euro cents.  Land Securities Group Plc (LAND)  : The U.K.’s largest
real estate investment trust by value cut its vacancy rate to
3.9 percent at the end of June from 4.2 percent at the end of
March after attracting tenants. It will pay a quarterly dividend
of 7.2 pence a share. The stock declined 1.4 percent to 866
pence.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : Royal Bank of Scotland
Group Plc’s head of restructuring and risk, Nathan Bostock, is
leaving to join Lloyds as the head of its wholesale banking
operation, the company said in a statement. The stock slumped
7.5 percent to 41.35 pence.  Johnson Matthey Plc (JMAT)  : Underlying pretax profit
rose 19 percent to 98.2 million pounds ($158 million) in the
fiscal first quarter, the chemicals company said in a statement.
The stock rose 3.3 percent to 1,938 pence  IG Group Holdings Plc (IGG)  : The spread-betting company
said full-year adjusted pretax profit rose 3.4 percent to 163
million pounds. IG said it will pay a final dividend of 14.75
pence a share. The stock fell 5.4 percent to 411.4 pence.  Vodafone Plc (VOD LN): Dutch competition regulator NMa
approved Vodafone’s takeover of Macintosh Retail Group NV’s
BelCompany under conditions, according to a statement on its
website today. The stock fell 1.1 percent to 157.25 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
